In[7]:
for i, col in enumerate(merged_df.columns):
    if merged_df[col].dtype != 'object':
        Q1 = merged_df[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = merged_df[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        # Define outlier thresholds
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

        # Identify outliers
        outliers = merged_df[(merged_df[col] < lower_bound) | (merged_df[col] > upper_bound)]

        print("Outliers:")
        print(outliers[[col]])
        
        # Check the percentage of outliers
        outlier_percentage = len(outliers) / len(merged_df) * 100
        print(f"Percentage of Outliers in {col}: {outlier_percentage:.2f}%")

        # Insert a separatar after each column
        print("xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx\n")

# Further reading into Revenue Growth outliers
revenue_growth_Q1 = merged_df['Revenue Growth'].quantile(0.25)
revenue_growth_Q3 = merged_df['Revenue Growth'].quantile(0.75)
revenue_growth_IQR = revenue_growth_Q3 - revenue_growth_Q1
revenue_growth_lower_bound = revenue_growth_Q1 - 1.5 * revenue_growth_IQR
revenue_growth_upper_bound = revenue_growth_Q3 + 1.5 * revenue_growth_IQR

# Identify outliers
revenue_growth_outliers = merged_df[
    (merged_df['Revenue Growth'] < revenue_growth_lower_bound) | 
    (merged_df['Revenue Growth'] > revenue_growth_upper_bound)
]['Revenue Growth']

# Calculate statistics for the outliers
if not revenue_growth_outliers.empty:
    min_outlier = revenue_growth_outliers.min()
    mean_outlier = revenue_growth_outliers.mean()
    max_outlier = revenue_growth_outliers.max()

    print(f"Min Outlier: {min_outlier:.2f}")
    print(f"Mean Outlier: {mean_outlier:.2f}")
    print(f"Max Outlier: {max_outlier:.2f}")
else:
    print("No outliers detected in Revenue Growth.")

Min Outlier: 2.86
Mean Outlier: 21.77
Max Outlier: 1635.02

Outlier Distribution:

Most columns have no outliers which indicate data consistency. Operating Income, Net Income, Operating Expenses and EBITDA show small percentages of outliers and are likely natural variations of financial metrics. This also indicates that the operational metrics are stable and reliable.

Revenue Growth:

12.13% of the data in Revenue Growth are identified as outliers. Revenue growth rates can have high variability as a result of market conditions and company expansions.

merged_df is also sorted by Stock & Year to show the year-on-year growth in Revenue more clearly.

Hence, this does not reflect an issue with the data or affect the consistency of the other metrics in the dataset.

Frequency Distribution of Metrics

In[18]:
# For each column, create a histogram of counts to check distribution of skew
plt.figure(figsize=(10, len(merged_df.columns) * 2))

# Iterate over numeric columns
for i, col in enumerate(merged_df.columns):
    if merged_df[col].dtype != 'object':
        plt.subplot(len(merged_df.columns), 1, i + 1)
        sns.histplot(
            merged_df[col],
            kde=True,
            color='g',
            bins=40,
            label='Histogram'
        )
        plt.title(col)
        plt.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Operating Income, Net Income & EBITDA:

The distribution is heavily skewed to the right. Most values are concentrated to the lower end with fewer data points reaching into the higher ranges. This could indicate that most companies have lower profits while only a few companies are extremely profitable.

Revenue:

Revenue is evenly spread out from the low to middle range, but have low counts on the extreme right. Only a few companies generated exceptionally high revenue.

Gross Profit Ratio & Net Income Ratio:

While both ratios have high number of data points in the middle range, Gross Profit Ratio is slightly more right-skewed than Net Income Ratio. This means that fewer companies achieve exceptionally high net profit margins compared to gross profit margins.

This is expected because net income accounts for additional expenses like operating costs, interest and taxes, which lowers the profit margin.

Operating Expenses & Cost of Revenue:

Operating Expenses (selling, general and administrative expenses) & Cost of Revenue (direct cost of goods/services) cluster in the low to middle range, but skew to the right afterwards.

Most companies in this dataset operate with moderate expenses, which also aligns with the fact that they generate lower revenues.

The right skew in both expense types suggest that only a few companies have exceptionally high expenses, which can be due to highly large-scale and complex businesses with high direct and operating costs.

In[29]:
# Aggregate total revenue by 'Year'
summary = merged_df.groupby('Year').agg({
    'Revenue': 'sum'
}).reset_index()

# Calculate revenue growth as the percentage change from the previous year
summary['Revenue Growth'] = summary['Revenue'].pct_change() * 100

# Create a combo chart: Revenue as bars and Revenue Growth as a line
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

# Plot Revenue as bars
ax1.bar(summary['Year'], summary['Revenue'], color='blue', label='Total Revenue', alpha=0.6)
ax1.set_xlabel('Year', fontsize=12)
ax1.set_ylabel('Total Revenue', fontsize=12, color='blue')
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='blue')

# Create a second y-axis for Revenue Growth
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.plot(summary['Year'], summary['Revenue Growth'], marker='o', color='black', label='Revenue Growth (%)')
ax2.set_ylabel('Revenue Growth (%)', fontsize=12, color='black')
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='black')

# Title and grid
plt.title('Total Revenue and Revenue Growth Over Time', fontsize=14)
ax1.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Label all years on the x-axis
ax1.set_xticks(summary['Year'])
ax1.set_xticklabels(summary['Year'], rotation=45, fontsize=10)

# Display the chart
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

We see that the total revenue jumped by nearly 100% from 2022-2023. Is this an overall trend observed in most companies or are specific companies making exceptionally high revenue?

Revenue frequencies were around 2 times more in 2022-2023 than 2020-2021 & 2024.

Since the skew on the right in 2022-2023 is relatively small, the jump in revenue is an increase across most companies rather than a few outliers.

Most companies also generated less revenue in 2024, a decrease from 2022-2023.

Top 5 Companies by Revenue (2020-2024)

We are also interested to observe how the Top 5 companies with the highest revenue performed from 2020 to 2024.

In[8]:
# Aggregate total revenue by 'Year' and 'Stock'
df_revenue = merged_df.groupby(['Year', 'Stock']).agg({
    'Revenue': 'sum'
}).reset_index()

# Filter data for the years 2020-2024
df_revenue_filtered = df_revenue[df_revenue['Year'].between(2020, 2024)]

# Aggregate total revenue by company (Stock) across all years to find the top 5
top_5_revenue = df_revenue_filtered.groupby('Stock')['Revenue'].sum().nlargest(5).index

# Filter the data for the top 5 companies
df_top_5_revenue = df_revenue_filtered[df_revenue_filtered['Stock'].isin(top_5_revenue)]

# Create a line chart for top 5 companies by Revenue over time (2020-2024)
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

for stock in top_5_revenue:
    company_data = df_top_5_revenue[df_top_5_revenue['Stock'] == stock]
    plt.plot(company_data['Year'], company_data['Revenue'], marker='o', label=stock)

# Title and labels
plt.title('Top 5 Companies by Revenue Over Time (2020-2024)', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Revenue', fontsize=12)
plt.legend(title='Company (Stock)', fontsize=10)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.xticks(ticks=range(2020, 2025))  # Label years 2020-2024 on x-axis
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

IKSM Performance: IKSM reached its peak revenue in 2022 but experienced a decline during 2023 and 2024. This suggests potential challenges, such as product or service issues or increased discounts that may have impacted revenue.

Peer Companies: The companies VIDHD, IQUUG, ZPIO, and XDPVP outperformed IKSM in revenue in 2023. However, by 2024, only IQUUG and ZPIO continued to generate revenue comparable to IKSM. This trend hints that these five companies might belong to the same industry, as IKSM's contrasting performance from 2022 to 2023 is notable compared to the other companies.

The period of 2022-2023 was likely marked by a strong economy, with many businesses expanding their operations. This broader economic growth may have influenced revenue trends across companies.

This can indicate that expenses could be higher for these data points which could have resulted in lower Net Income.

In[7]:
# Filter data for the necessary columns and ensure it's sorted by Year
ratios_df = merged_df[['Year', 'Gross Profit Ratio', 'Net Income Ratio', 'Operating Income Ratio', 'Operating Expense Ratio']].groupby('Year').mean().reset_index()

# Create a line chart
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))

# Plot each ratio
plt.plot(ratios_df['Year'], ratios_df['Gross Profit Ratio'], marker='o', label='Gross Profit Ratio', color='blue')
plt.plot(ratios_df['Year'], ratios_df['Net Income Ratio'], marker='o', label='Net Income Ratio', color='green')
plt.plot(ratios_df['Year'], ratios_df['Operating Expense Ratio'], marker='o', label='Operating Expense Ratio', color='red')
plt.plot(ratios_df['Year'], ratios_df['Operating Income Ratio'], marker='o', label='Operating Income Ratio', color='brown')
           
# Chart title and labels
plt.title('Profit Performance Over Years', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Ratio', fontsize=12)

# Grid, legend, and layout adjustments
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.legend(title='Metrics', fontsize=10)
plt.xticks(ratios_df['Year'], rotation=45)

# Display the chart
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Gross Profit Ratio is consistently the highest, above Operating Expense Ratio and Net Income Ratio. This suggests stability in both profitability and expenditure relative to revenue across the years.

Operating Income Ratio also mirrors Net Income Ratio, which could indicate either minimal debt (so the company's profit from its operations is almost entirely contributing to net income without influence from interest expense) or low operating margins (lack diversified income streams).

It is expected that Net Income Ratio is the lowest because it accounts for additional expenses which reduce Net Income.

Checking Interest Expense

To investigate whether most companies have minimal debt, we can check whether interest expense is low relative to the operating income.

If it is low, then it suggests minimal debt. If it is high, then debt could be significant.

In[10]:
merged_df['Interest Coverage Ratio'] = merged_df['Operating Income'] / merged_df['Interest Expense']

# Group by 'Stock' and calculate the average Interest Coverage Ratio for each company
company_debt_data = merged_df.groupby('Stock')['Interest Coverage Ratio'].mean().reset_index()

# Classify companies based on Interest Coverage Ratio thresholds
high_debt_companies = company_debt_data[company_debt_data['Interest Coverage Ratio'] < 1]
moderate_debt_companies = company_debt_data[(company_debt_data['Interest Coverage Ratio'] >= 1) & 
                                            (company_debt_data['Interest Coverage Ratio'] <= 2)]
low_debt_companies = company_debt_data[company_debt_data['Interest Coverage Ratio'] > 2]

All companies in the dataset have high operating income relative to interest expense, meaning low debt.

Next, we will find out the distribution of operating income ratios across companies.

Most companies operate with moderate margin, while only a small percentage have high margins.

4. Analyzing Expenses

Expense Type Breakdown

We are interested in the expense type distribution (Cost of Revenue, Operating Expenses, Depreciation & Amortization) to observe how they compare across the years.

Cost of Revenue = Revenue - Gross Profit

Operating Expenses = Gross Profit - Operating Income

Depreciation & Amortization = EBITDA - Operating Income

Since all companies from the dataset do not suffer from high debt, all of their net income comes from core business operations and not from financing. Hence, Interest Expense is not included.

In[6]:
# Calculate proportions of each category
expense_proportions = merged_df.groupby('Year')[['Cost of Revenue', 'Operating Expenses', 'Depreciation & Amortization']].sum()
expense_proportions['Total'] = expense_proportions.sum(axis=1)
expense_proportions['Cost of Revenue %'] = expense_proportions['Cost of Revenue'] / expense_proportions['Total'] * 100
expense_proportions['Operating Expenses %'] = expense_proportions['Operating Expenses'] / expense_proportions['Total'] * 100
expense_proportions['Depreciation & Amortization %'] = expense_proportions['Depreciation & Amortization'] / expense_proportions['Total'] * 100

# Add grid for better readability
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Display the chart
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Cost of Revenue is consistently higher than Operating Expenses and Depreciation & Amortization. This means that production & procurement costs (Cost of Revenue) are the most significant expense besides admin, marketing and general expenses (Operating Expenses).

The low D&A also suggests that these companies do not invest in assets that are vulnerable to depreciation.

Gross Profit vs Cost of Revenue as a Proportion of Revenue

Since Cost of Revenue + Gross Profit = Revenue, it is useful to see whether the gross profit margin is healthy versus the cost of revenue.

In[15]:
mean_expense_proportions = merged_df.groupby('Year')[['Revenue', 'Gross Profit', 'Cost of Revenue']].mean()
mean_expense_proportions = mean_expense_proportions.rename(columns={
    'Revenue': 'Average Revenue',
    'Gross Profit': 'Average Gross Profit',
    'Cost of Revenue': 'Average Cost of Revenue'
})
mean_expense_proportions['Average Gross Profit (Proportion of Revenue)'] = mean_expense_proportions['Average Gross Profit'] / mean_expense_proportions['Average Revenue']
mean_expense_proportions['Average Cost of Revenue (Proportion of Revenue)'] = mean_expense_proportions['Average Cost of Revenue'] / mean_expense_proportions['Average Revenue']

Gross Profit Ratio and Cost of Revenue seem to move together and remain largely stable over the years, with no significant increase or decrease in overall gross profit or cost.

The stable Cost of Revenue means that companies have not significantly reduced their cost base.

Companies can look for other opportunities to reduce production costs or improve resource allocation to lower Cost of Revenue, while explore other revenue-generating strategies to push Gross Profit Ratio even higher.
